{
  "texts": [
    "This reflects that public consciousness is overwhelmed with knowledge claims and cannot evaluate each, so that a consensus is formed around the sum of all voices.",
    "Unlike the individual innovator who has a narrow focus and observes whether her patent ultimately generates value, the public sphere has limited attention and is forced to accept the aggregate contributions of the marketplace of ideas.",
    "As a result, individuals' investments in innovation have positive spillovers to the extent they can move public knowledge towards the truth.",
    "However, if too many people invest in 'popular' or 'central' knowledge by sampling from the truncated distribution, this can have a negative externality, by distorting public knowledge towards the center and thinning the tails.",
    "6 We also introduce the possibility of generational turnover in some models to explore the impact on knowledge collapse."
  ]
}